<p>V. Ovid, <i>Metamorphoses</i>, VI, Philomela. [Eliot's
        note] Eliot refers to the story of Philomela who was
        raped by Tereus, the husband of her sister Procne. All
        three are in the end turned into birds; Procne and
        Philomel into nightingales, and Tereus into a lapwing. </p>
